# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wirelesshart
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The **HART Communication Protocol (Highway Addressable Remote Transducer)** is a hybrid analog+digital industrial automation open protocol.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Its most notable advantage is that it can communicate over legacy 4–20 mA analog instrumentation current loops, sharing the pair of wires used by the analog-only host systems.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] HART is widely used in process and instrumentation systems ranging from small automation applications up to highly sophisticated industrial applications.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Based on the OSI model, HART resides at Layer 7, the Application Layer.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] When sent over 4–20 mA it uses a Bell 202 for layer 1.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] But it is often converted to RS485 or RS232.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] According to Emerson, due to the huge installation base of 4–20 mA systems throughout the world, the HART Protocol is one of the most popular industrial protocols today.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] HART protocol has made a good transition protocol for users who wished to use the legacy 4–20 mA signals, but wanted to implement a "smart" protocol.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The protocol was developed by Rosemount Inc., built off the Bell 202 early communications standard in the mid-1980s as a proprietary digital communication protocol for their smart field instruments.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Soon it evolved into HART and in 1986 it was made an open protocol.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Since then, the capabilities of the protocol have been enhanced by successive revisions to the specification.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] There are two main operational modes of HART instruments: point-to-point (analog/digital) mode, and multi-drop mode.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] In point-to-point mode the digital signals are overlaid on the 4–20 mA loop current.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Both the 4–20 mA current and the digital signal are valid signalling protocols between the controller and measuring instrument or final control element.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The polling address of the instrument is set to "0".
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Only one instrument can be put on each instrument cable signal pair.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] One signal, generally specified by the user, is specified to be the 4–20 mA signal.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Other signals are sent digitally on top of the 4–20 mA signal.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] For example, pressure can be sent as 4–20 mA, representing a range of pressures, and temperature can be sent digitally over the same wires.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] In point-to-point mode, the digital part of the HART protocol can be seen as a kind of digital current loop interface.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] In multi-drop mode the analog loop current is fixed at 4 mA and it is possible to have more than one instrument on a signal loop.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] HART revisions 3 through 5 allowed polling addresses of the instruments to be in the range 1–15.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] HART revision 6 allowed addresses 1 to 63; HART revision 7 allows addresses 0 to 63.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Each instrument must have a unique address.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Currently all the newer devices implement five byte preamble, since anything greater reduces the communication speed.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] However, masters are responsible for backwards support.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Master communication to a new device starts with the maximum preamble length (20 bytes) and is later reduced once the preamble size for the current device is determined.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] This byte contains the Master number and specifies that the communication packet is starting.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] normally it set if Expansion field is used, normally 0.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Specifies the destination address as implemented in one of the HART schemes.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The original addressing scheme used only four bits to specify the device address, which limited the number of devices to 16 including the master.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The newer scheme utilizes 38 bits to specify the device address.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] This address is requested from the device using either Command 0, or Command 11.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] This is a one byte numerical value representing which command is to be executed.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Command 0 and Command 11 are used to request the device number.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Specifies the number of communication data bytes to follow.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The status field is absent for the master and is two bytes for the slave.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] This field is used by the slave to inform the master whether it completed the task and what its current health status is.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Data contained in this field depends on the command to be executed.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Checksum is composed of an XOR of all the bytes starting from the start byte and ending with the last byte of the data field, including those bytes.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Each manufacturer that participates in the HART convention is assigned an identification number.
[src:wirelesshart/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] This number is communicated as part of the basic device identification command used when first connecting to a device.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE standard 802.15.4 is intended to offer the fundamental lower network layers of a type of wireless personal area network (WPAN), which focuses on low-cost, low-speed ubiquitous communication between devices.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] It can be contrasted with other approaches, such as Wi-Fi, which offers more bandwidth and requires more power.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The emphasis is on very low-cost communication of nearby devices with little to no underlying infrastructure, intending to exploit this to lower power consumption even more.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The basic framework conceives a 10-meter communications range with line of sight at a transfer rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Bandwidth tradeoffs are possible to favor more radically embedded devices with even lower power requirements for increased battery operating time, through the definition of not one, but several physical layers.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Lower transfer rates of 20 and 40 kbit/s were initially defined, with the 100 kbit/s rate being added in the current revision.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Even lower rates can be used, which results in lower power consumption.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] As already mentioned, the main goal of IEEE 802.15.4 regarding WPANs is the emphasis on achieving low manufacturing and operating costs through the use of relatively simple transceivers, while enabling application flexibility and adaptability.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Integrated support for secure communications.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Power management functions to adjust compromises of link speed and quality and energy detection.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Support for time- and data-rate–sensitive applications through the ability to operate with either CSMA/CA or TDMA access modes.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The TDMA mode of operation is supported via the GTS feature of the standard.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE 802.15.4-conformant devices may use one of three possible frequency bands for operation (868/915/2450 MHz).
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Devices are designed to interact with each other over a conceptually simple wireless network.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The definition of the network layers is based on the OSI model; although only the lower layers are defined in the standard, interaction with upper layers is intended, possibly using an IEEE 802.2 logical link control sublayer accessing the MAC through a convergence sublayer.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Implementations may rely on external devices or be purely embedded, self-functioning devices.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The *physical layer* (PHY) provides the data transmission service.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] It also, provides an interface to the *physical layer management entity*, which offers access to every physical layer management function and maintains a database of information on related personal area networks.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Thus, the PHY manages the physical radio transceiver, performs channel selection along with energy and signal management functions.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] An optional alternative 868/915 MHz layer is defined using a combination of binary keying and amplitude-shift keying (thus based on parallel, not sequential, spread spectrum; PSSS).
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Dynamic switching between supported 868/915 MHz PHYs is possible.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Beyond these three bands, the IEEE 802.15.4c study group considered the newly opened 314–316 MHz, 430–434 MHz, and 779–787 MHz bands in China, while the IEEE 802.15 Task Group 4d defined an amendment to to support the new 950–956 MHz band in Japan.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The first standard amendments by these groups were released in April 2009.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] IEEE 802.15.4e was chartered to define a MAC amendment to the existing standard 802.15.4-2006 which adopts a channel hopping strategy to improve support for the industrial market.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Channel hopping increases robustness against external interference and persistent multi-path fading.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] On February 6, 2012, the IEEE Standards Association Board approved IEEE 802.15.4e which concluded all Task Group 4e efforts.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The medium access control (MAC) enables the transmission of MAC frames through the use of the physical channel.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Besides the data service, it offers a management interface and itself manages access to the physical channel and network beaconing.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] It also controls frame validation, guarantees time slots and handles node associations.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Finally, it offers hook points for secure services.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Note that the IEEE 802.15 standard does *not* use 802.1d or IEEE standard 802.15.4q-2016; i.e., it does not exchange standard Ethernet frames.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The physical frame-format is specified in IEEE standard 802.15.4-2011 in section 5.2.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] It is tailored to the fact that most IEEE 802.15.4 PHYs only support frames of up to 127 bytes (adaptation layer protocols such as the IETF's 6LoWPAN provide fragmentation schemes to support larger network layer packets).
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] No higher-level layers or interoperability sublayers are defined in the standard.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Other specifications, such as Zigbee, SNAP, and 6LoWPAN/Thread, build on this standard.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] RIOT, OpenWSN, TinyOS, Unison RTOS, DSPnano RTOS, nanoQplus, Contiki and Zephyr operating systems also use some components of IEEE standard 802.15.4-2020 hardware and software.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The standard defines two types of network node.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The first one is the **full-function device** (FFD).
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] It can serve as the coordinator of a personal area network just as it may function as a common node.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] It implements a general model of communication which allows it to talk to any other device: it may also relay messages, in which case it is dubbed a coordinator (PAN coordinator when it is in charge of the whole network).
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] On the other hand, there are **reduced-function devices** (RFD).
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] These are meant to be extremely simple devices with very modest resource and communication requirements; due to this, they can only communicate with FFDs and can never act as coordinators.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Networks can be built as either peer-to-peer or star networks.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] However, every network needs at least one FFD to work as the coordinator of the network.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Networks are thus formed by groups of devices separated by suitable distances.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Each device has a unique 64-bit identifier, and if some conditions are met, short 16-bit identifiers can be used within a restricted environment.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Namely, within each PAN domain, communications will probably use short identifiers.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] A more structured **star** pattern is also supported, where the coordinator of the network will necessarily be the central node.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Such a network can originate when an FFD decides to create its own PAN and declare itself its coordinator, after choosing a unique PAN identifier.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] After that, other devices can join the network, which is fully independent from all other star networks.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Frames are the basic unit of data transport, of which there are four fundamental types (data, acknowledgment, beacon and MAC command frames), which provide a reasonable tradeoff between simplicity and robustness.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Additionally, a superframe structure, defined by the coordinator, may be used, in which case two beacons act as its limits and provide synchronization to other devices as well as configuration information.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] A superframe consists of sixteen equal-length slots, which can be further divided into an active part and an inactive part, during which the coordinator may enter power saving mode, not needing to control its network.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Within superframes contention occurs between their limits, and is resolved by CSMA/CA.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Every transmission must end before the arrival of the second beacon.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] As mentioned before, applications with well-defined bandwidth needs can use up to seven domains of one or more contentionless guaranteed time slots, trailing at the end of the superframe.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The first part of the superframe must be sufficient to give service to the network structure and its devices.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Superframes are typically utilized within the context of low-latency devices, whose associations must be kept even if inactive for long periods of time.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Data transfers to the coordinator require a beacon synchronization phase, if applicable, followed by CSMA/CA transmission (by means of slots if superframes are in use); acknowledgment is optional.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Data transfers from the coordinator usually follow device requests: if beacons are in use, these are used to signal requests; the coordinator acknowledges the request and then sends the data in packets which are acknowledged by the device.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The same is done when superframes are not in use, only in this case there are no beacons to keep track of pending messages.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Point-to-point networks may either use unslotted CSMA/CA or synchronization mechanisms; in this case, communication between any two devices is possible, whereas in "structured" modes one of the devices must be the network coordinator.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] In general, all implemented procedures follow a typical request-confirm/indication-response classification.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] The physical medium is accessed through a CSMA/CA access method.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Networks which are not using beaconing mechanisms utilize an unslotted variation which is based on the listening of the medium, leveraged by a random exponential backoff algorithm; acknowledgments do not adhere to this discipline.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Common data transmission utilizes unallocated slots when beaconing is in use; again, confirmations do not follow the same process.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Confirmation messages may be optional under certain circumstances, in which case a success assumption is made.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Whatever the case, if a device is unable to process a frame at a given time, it simply does not confirm its reception: timeout-based retransmission can be performed a number of times, following after that a decision of whether to abort or keep trying.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Because the predicted environment of these devices demands maximization of battery life, the protocols tend to favor the methods which lead to it, implementing periodic checks for pending messages, the frequency of which depends on application needs.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Regarding secure communications, the MAC sublayer offers facilities which can be harnessed by upper layers to achieve the desired level of security.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Higher-layer processes may specify keys to perform symmetric cryptography to protect the payload and restrict it to a group of devices or just a point-to-point link; these groups of devices can be specified in access control lists.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] Furthermore, MAC computes *freshness checks* between successive receptions to ensure that presumably old frames, or data which is no longer considered valid, does not transcend to higher layers.
[src:wirelesshart/ieee-802-15-4] In addition to this secure mode, there is another, insecure MAC mode, which allows access control lists merely as a means to decide on the acceptance of frames according to their (presumed) source.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] A **mesh network** is a network topology in which the infrastructure nodes (i.e., bridges, switches, and other infrastructure devices) connect directly, dynamically and non-hierarchically to as many other nodes as possible and cooperate with one another to efficiently route data to and from hosts.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] This lack of dependency on one node allows for every node to participate in the relay of information.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] Mesh networks dynamically self-organize and self-configure, which can reduce installation overhead.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] The ability to self-configure enables dynamic distribution of workloads, particularly in the event that a few nodes should fail.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] This, in turn, contributes to fault-tolerance and reduced maintenance costs.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] Mesh topology may be contrasted with conventional star/tree network topologies in which the bridges/switches are directly linked to only a small subset of other bridges/switches, and the links between these infrastructure neighbours are hierarchical.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] While star-and-tree topologies are very well established, highly standardized and vendor-neutral, vendors of mesh network devices have not yet all agreed on common standards, and interoperability between devices from different vendors is not yet assured.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] Mesh networks can relay messages using either a *flooding* or a *routing* technique, which makes them different from non-mesh networks.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] A routed message is propagated along a path by *hopping* from node to node until it reaches its destination.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] To ensure that all its paths are available, the network must allow for continuous connections and must reconfigure itself around broken paths, using *self-healing* algorithms such as Shortest Path Bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links).
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] Self-healing allows a routing-based network to operate when a node breaks down or when a connection becomes unreliable.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] The network is typically quite reliable, as there is often more than one path between a source and a destination in the network.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] Although mostly used in wireless situations, this concept can also apply to wired networks and to software interaction.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] A mesh network whose nodes are all connected to each other is a fully connected network.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] Fully connected wired networks are more secure and reliable: problems in a cable affect only the two nodes attached to it.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] In such networks, however, the number of cables, and therefore the cost, goes up rapidly as the number of nodes increases.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] Shortest path bridging and TRILL each allow Ethernet switches to be connected in a mesh topology and allow for all paths to be active.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] IP routing supports multiple paths from source to destination.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] A wireless mesh network (WMN) is a network made up of radio nodes organized in a mesh topology.
[src:wirelesshart/mesh-networking] It can also be a form of wireless ad hoc network.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In IPC, control theory provides the theoretical framework to understand system dynamics, predict outcomes and design control strategies to ensure predetermined objectives, utilizing concepts like feedback loops, stability analysis and controller design.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] On the other hand, the physical apparatus of IPC, based on automation technologies, consists of several components.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Firstly, a network of sensors continuously measure various process variables (such as temperature, pressure, etc.) and product quality variables.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] This creates a continuous closed-loop cycle of measurement, comparison, control action, and re-evaluation which guarantees that the process remains within established parameters.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The HMI (Human-Machine Interface) acts as the "control panel" for the IPC system where small number of human operators can monitor the process and make informed decisions regarding adjustments.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] IPCs can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel (controlled environment tank for mixing, separating, reacting, or storing materials in industrial processes.) to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control feedback loops.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] IPC provides several critical benefits to manufacturing companies.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] By maintaining a tight control over key process variables, it helps reduce energy use, minimize waste and shorten downtime for peak efficiency and reduced costs.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] It ensures consistent and improved product quality with little variability, which satisfies the customers and strengthens the company's reputation.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] It improves safety by detecting and alerting human operators about potential issues early, thus preventing accidents, equipment failures, process disruptions and costly downtime.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Analyzing trends and behaviors in the vast amounts of data collected real-time helps engineers identify areas of improvement, refine control strategies and continuously enhance production efficiency using a data-driven approach.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] IPC is used across a wide range of industries where precise control is important.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The applications can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel, to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control loops.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In automotive manufacturing, IPC ensures consistent quality by meticulously controlling processes like welding and painting.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Mining operations are optimized with IPC monitoring ore crushing and adjusting conveyor belt speeds for maximum output.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Dredging benefits from precise control of suction pressure, dredging depth and sediment discharge rate by IPC, ensuring efficient and sustainable practices.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Pulp and paper production leverages IPC to regulate chemical processes (e.g., pH and bleach concentration) and automate paper machine operations to control paper sheet moisture content and drying temperature for consistent quality.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In chemical plants, it ensures the safe and efficient production of chemicals by controlling temperature, pressure and reaction rates.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Oil refineries use it to smoothly convert crude oil into gasoline and other petroleum products.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In power plants, it helps maintain stable operating conditions necessary for a continuous electricity supply.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In food and beverage production, it helps ensure consistent texture, safety and quality.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Pharmaceutical companies relies on it to produce life-saving drugs safely and effectively.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The development of large industrial process control systems has been instrumental in enabling the design of large high volume and complex processes, which could not be otherwise economically or safely operated.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Early process control breakthroughs came most frequently in the form of water control devices.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Ktesibios of Alexandria is credited for inventing float valves to regulate water level of water clocks in the 3rd century BC.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In the 1st century AD, Heron of Alexandria invented a water valve similar to the fill valve used in modern toilets.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Later process controls inventions involved basic physics principles.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel invented a bimetallic thermostat for controlling the temperature in a furnace.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In 1681, Denis Papin discovered the pressure inside a vessel could be regulated by placing weights on top of the vessel lid.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In 1745, Edmund Lee created the fantail to improve windmill efficiency; a fantail was a smaller windmill placed 90° of the larger fans to keep the face of the windmill pointed directly into the oncoming wind.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] With the dawn of the Industrial Revolution in the 1760s, process controls inventions were aimed to replace human operators with mechanized processes.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In 1784, Oliver Evans created a water-powered flourmill which operated using buckets and screw conveyors.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Henry Ford applied the same theory in 1910 when the assembly line was created to decrease human intervention in the automobile production process.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] For continuously variable process control it was not until 1922 that a formal control law for what we now call PID control or three-term control was first developed using theoretical analysis, by Russian American engineer Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Minorsky was researching and designing automatic ship steering for the US Navy and based his analysis on observations of a helmsman.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] He noted the helmsman steered the ship based not only on the current course error, but also on past error, as well as the current rate of change; this was then given a mathematical treatment by Minorsky.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] His goal was stability, not general control, which simplified the problem significantly.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] While proportional control provided stability against small disturbances, it was insufficient for dealing with a steady disturbance, notably a stiff gale (due to steady-state error), which required adding the integral term.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Finally, the derivative term was added to improve stability and control.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] However this required a large manpower resource to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Effectively this was the centralization of all the localized panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] These could be distributed around the plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The distributed control system (DCS) was born.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels in a large process using processor and computer-based control.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] To determine the fundamental model for any process, the inputs and outputs of the system are defined differently than for other chemical processes.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The balance equations are defined by the control inputs and outputs rather than the material inputs.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The control model is a set of equations used to predict the behavior of a system and can help determine what the response to change will be.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The state variable (x) is a measurable variable that is a good indicator of the state of the system, such as temperature (energy balance), volume (mass balance) or concentration (component balance).
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Input variable (u) is a specified variable that commonly include flow rates.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The entering and exiting flows are both considered control inputs.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The control input can be classified as a manipulated, disturbance, or unmonitored variable.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Parameters (p) are usually a physical limitation and something that is fixed for the system, such as the vessel volume or the viscosity of the material.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Output (y) is the metric used to determine the behavior of the system.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The control output can be classified as measured, unmeasured, or unmonitored.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Processes can be characterized as batch, continuous, or hybrid.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Batch applications require that specific quantities of raw materials be combined in specific ways for particular duration to produce an intermediate or end result.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] One example is the production of adhesives and glues, which normally require the mixing of raw materials in a heated vessel for a period of time to form a quantity of end product.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Other important examples are the production of food, beverages and medicine.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Batch processes are generally used to produce a relatively low to intermediate quantity of product per year (a few pounds to millions of pounds).
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] A continuous physical system is represented through variables that are smooth and uninterrupted in time.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The control of the water temperature in a heating jacket, for example, is an example of continuous process control.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Some important continuous processes are the production of fuels, chemicals and plastics.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Continuous processes in manufacturing are used to produce very large quantities of product per year (millions to billions of pounds).
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Such controls use feedback such as in the PID controller A PID Controller includes proportional, integrating, and derivative controller functions.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Applications having elements of batch and continuous process control are often called hybrid applications.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The fundamental building block of any industrial control system is the control loop, which controls just one process variable.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] An example is shown in the accompanying diagram, where the flow rate in a pipe is controlled by a PID controller, assisted by what is effectively a cascaded loop in the form of a valve servo-controller to ensure correct valve positioning.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Some large systems may have several hundreds or thousands of control loops.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] In complex processes the loops are interactive, so that the operation of one loop may affect the operation of another.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The system diagram for representing control loops is a Piping and instrumentation diagram.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Commonly used control systems include programmable logic controller (PLC), Distributed Control System (DCS) or SCADA.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] If a control valve were used to hold level in a tank, the level controller would compare the equivalent reading of a level sensor to the level setpoint and determine whether more or less valve opening was necessary to keep the level constant.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] A cascaded flow controller could then calculate the change in the valve position.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The economic nature of many products manufactured in batch and continuous processes require highly efficient operation due to thin margins.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The competing factor in process control is that products must meet certain specifications in order to be satisfactory.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] These specifications can come in two forms: a minimum and maximum for a property of the material or product, or a range within which the property must be.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] All loops are susceptible to disturbances and therefore a buffer must be used on process set points to ensure disturbances do not cause the material or product to go out of specifications.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] This buffer comes at an economic cost (i.e. additional processing, maintaining elevated or depressed process conditions, etc.).
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Process efficiency can be enhanced by reducing the margins necessary to ensure product specifications are met.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] This can be done by improving the control of the process to minimize the effect of disturbances on the process.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] The efficiency is improved in a two step method of narrowing the variance and shifting the target.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Margins can be narrowed through various process upgrades (i.e. equipment upgrades, enhanced control methods, etc.).
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Once margins are narrowed, an economic analysis can be done on the process to determine how the set point target is to be shifted.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Less conservative process set points lead to increased economic efficiency.
[src:wirelesshart/process-control] Effective process control strategies increase the competitive advantage of manufacturers who employ them.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] These are similar to wireless ad hoc networks in the sense that they rely on wireless connectivity and spontaneous formation of networks so that sensor data can be transported wirelessly.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs monitor physical conditions, such as temperature, sound, and pressure.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Modern networks are bi-directional, both collecting data and enabling control of sensor activity.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The development of these networks was motivated by military applications such as battlefield surveillance.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Such networks are used in industrial and consumer applications, such as industrial process monitoring and control and machine health monitoring and agriculture.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] A WSN is built of "nodes" – from a few to hundreds or thousands, where each node is connected to other sensors.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Each such node typically has several parts: a radio transceiver with an internal antenna or connection to an external antenna, a microcontroller, an electronic circuit for interfacing with the sensors and an energy source, usually a battery or an embedded form of energy harvesting.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] A sensor node might vary in size from a shoebox to (theoretically) a grain of dust, although microscopic dimensions have yet to be realized.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor node cost is similarly variable, ranging from a few to hundreds of dollars, depending on node sophistication.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Size and cost constraints constrain resources such as energy, memory, computational speed and communications bandwidth.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The topology of a WSN can vary from a simple star network to an advanced multi-hop wireless mesh network.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Propagation can employ routing or flooding.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] As of 2010, wireless sensor networks had deployed approximately 120 million remote units worldwide.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Area monitoring is a common application of WSNs.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] In area monitoring, the WSN is deployed over a region where some phenomenon is to be monitored.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] A military example is the use of sensors to detect enemy intrusion; a civilian example is the geo-fencing of gas or oil pipelines.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] There are several types of sensor networks for medical applications: implanted, wearable, and environment-embedded.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Implantable medical devices are those that are inserted inside the human body.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Wearable devices are used on the body surface of a human or just at close proximity of the user.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Environment-embedded systems employ sensors contained in the environment.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Possible applications include body position measurement, location of persons, overall monitoring of ill patients in hospitals and at home.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Devices embedded in the environment track the physical state of a person for continuous health diagnosis, using as input the data from a network of depth cameras, a sensing floor, or other similar devices.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Body-area networks can collect information about an individual's health, fitness, and energy expenditure.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] In health care applications the privacy and authenticity of user data has prime importance.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Especially due to the integration of sensor networks, with IoT, the user authentication becomes more challenging; however, a solution is presented in recent work.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been used to monitor various species and habitats, beginning with the Great Duck Island Deployment, including marmots, cane toads in Australia and zebras in Kenya.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] There are many applications in monitoring environmental parameters, examples of which are given below.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] They share the extra challenges of harsh environments and reduced power supply.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Experiments have shown that personal exposure to air pollution in cities can vary a lot.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, it is of interest to have higher temporal and spatial resolution of pollutants and particulates.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] For research purposes, wireless sensor networks have been deployed to monitor the concentration of dangerous gases for citizens (e.g., in London).
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] However, sensors for gases and particulate matter suffer from high unit-to-unit variability, cross-sensitivities, and (concept) drift.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Moreover, the quality of data is currently insufficient for trustworthy decision-making, as field calibration leads to unreliable measurement results, and frequent recalibration might be required.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] A possible solution could be blind calibration or the usage of mobile references.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] A network of Sensor Nodes can be installed in a forest to detect when a fire has started.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The nodes can be equipped with sensors to measure temperature, humidity and gases which are produced by fire in the trees or vegetation.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The early detection is crucial for a successful action of the firefighters; thanks to Wireless Sensor Networks, the fire brigade will be able to know when a fire is started and how it is spreading.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] A landslide detection system makes use of a wireless sensor network to detect the slight movements of soil and changes in various parameters that may occur before or during a landslide.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Through the data gathered it may be possible to know the impending occurrence of landslides long before it actually happens.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Water quality monitoring involves analyzing water properties in dams, rivers, lakes and oceans, as well as underground water reserves.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The use of many wireless distributed sensors enables the creation of a more accurate map of the water status, and allows the permanent deployment of monitoring stations in locations of difficult access, without the need of manual data retrieval.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks can be effective in preventing adverse consequences of natural disasters, like floods.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless nodes have been deployed successfully in rivers, where changes in water levels must be monitored in real time.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks have been developed for machinery condition-based maintenance (CBM) as they offer significant cost savings and enable new functionality.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensors can be placed in locations difficult or impossible to reach with a wired system, such as rotating machinery and untethered vehicles.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks also are used for the collection of data for monitoring of environmental information.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] This can be as simple as monitoring the temperature in a fridge or the level of water in overflow tanks in nuclear power plants.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The statistical information can then be used to show how systems have been working.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The advantage of WSNs over conventional loggers is the "live" data feed that is possible.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Monitoring the quality and level of water includes many activities such as checking the quality of underground or surface water and ensuring a country's water infrastructure for the benefit of both human and animal.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] It may be used to protect the wastage of water.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] WSN can be used to monitor the condition of civil infrastructure and related geo-physical processes close to real time, and over long periods through data logging, using appropriately interfaced sensors.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are used to monitor wine production, both in the field and the cellar.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The Wide Area Tracking System (WATS) is a prototype network for detecting a ground-based nuclear device such as a nuclear "briefcase bomb".
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] WATS is being developed at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (LLNL).
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would be made up of wireless gamma and neutron sensors connected through a communications network.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Data picked up by the sensors undergoes "data fusion", which converts the information into easily interpreted forms; this data fusion is the most important aspect of the system.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The data fusion process occurs *within* the sensor network rather than at a centralized computer and is performed by a specially developed algorithm based on Bayesian statistics.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] WATS would not use a centralized computer for analysis because researchers found that factors such as latency and available bandwidth tended to create significant bottlenecks.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Data processed in the field by the network itself (by transferring small amounts of data between neighboring sensors) is faster and makes the network more scalable.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] An important factor in WATS development is *ease of deployment*, since more sensors both improves the detection rate and reduces false alarms.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] WATS sensors could be deployed in permanent positions or mounted in vehicles for mobile protection of specific locations.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] One barrier to the implementation of WATS is the size, weight, energy requirements and cost of currently available wireless sensors.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The development of improved sensors is a major component of current research at the Nonproliferation, Arms Control, and International Security (NAI) Directorate at LLNL.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] House of Representatives' Military Research and Development Subcommittee on October 1, 1997, during a hearing on nuclear terrorism and countermeasures.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] On August 4, 1998, in a subsequent meeting of that subcommittee, Chairman Curt Weldon stated that research funding for WATS had been cut by the Clinton administration to a subsistence level and that the program had been poorly re-organized.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Studies show that using sensors for incident monitoring improve the response of firefighters and police to an unexpected situation.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] For an early detection of incidents we can use acoustic sensors to detect a spike in the noise of the city because of a possible accident, or use termic sensors to detect a possible fire.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Using low-power electronics, WSN:s can be cost-efficiently applied also in supply chains in various industries.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Cross-layer is becoming an important studying area for wireless communications.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The traditional layered approach does not have the ability to adapt to the environmental change.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Because of the interference between the different users, access conflicts, fading, and the change of environment in the wireless sensor networks, traditional layered approach for wired networks is not applicable to wireless networks.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] So the cross-layer can be used to make the optimal modulation to improve the transmission performance, such as data rate, energy efficiency, quality of service (QoS), etc.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Sensor nodes can be imagined as small computers which are extremely basic in terms of their interfaces and their components.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] They usually consist of a *processing unit* with limited computational power and limited memory, *sensors* or MEMS (including specific conditioning circuitry), a *communication device* (usually radio transceivers or alternatively optical), and a power source usually in the form of a battery.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Other possible inclusions are energy harvesting modules, secondary ASICs, and possibly secondary communication interface (e.g.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The base stations are one or more components of the WSN with much more computational, energy and communication resources.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] They act as a gateway between sensor nodes and the end user as they typically forward data from the WSN on to a server.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Other special components in routing based networks are routers, designed to compute, calculate and distribute the routing tables.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] One major challenge in a WSN is to produce *low cost* and *tiny* sensor nodes.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] There are an increasing number of small companies producing WSN hardware and the commercial situation can be compared to home computing in the 1970s.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Many of the nodes are still in the research and development stage, particularly their software.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Also inherent to sensor network adoption is the use of very low power methods for radio communication and data acquisition.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] In many applications, a WSN communicates with a local area network or wide area network through a gateway.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The Gateway acts as a bridge between the WSN and the other network.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] This enables data to be stored and processed by devices with more resources, for example, in a remotely located server.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] A wireless wide area network used primarily for low-power devices is known as a Low-Power Wide-Area Network (LPWAN).
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] There are several wireless standards and solutions for sensor node connectivity.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Thread and Zigbee can connect sensors operating at 2.4 GHz with a data rate of 250 kbit/s.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Many use a lower frequency to increase radio range (typically 1 km), for example Z-wave operates at 915 MHz (in North America) and in the EU 868 MHz has been widely used but these have a lower data rate (typically 50 kbit/s).
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The IEEE 802.15.4 working group provides a standard for low power device connectivity and commonly sensors and smart meters use one of these standards for connectivity.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] With the emergence of Internet of Things, many other proposals have been made to provide sensor connectivity.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] LoRa is a form of LPWAN which provides long range low power wireless connectivity for devices, which has been used in smart meters and other long range sensor applications.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] NarrowBand IOT and LTE-M can connect up to millions of sensors and devices using cellular technology.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Energy is the scarcest resource of WSN nodes, and it determines the lifetime of WSNs.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] WSNs may be deployed in large numbers in various environments, including remote and hostile regions, where ad hoc communications are a key component.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Lifetime maximization: Energy/Power Consumption of the sensing device should be minimized and sensor nodes should be energy efficient since their limited energy resource determines their lifetime.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] To conserve power, wireless sensor nodes normally power off both the radio transmitter and the radio receiver when not in use.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Wireless sensor networks are composed of low-energy, small-size, and low-range unattended sensor nodes.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Recently, it has been observed that by periodically turning on and off the sensing and communication capabilities of sensor nodes, we can significantly reduce the active time and thus prolong network lifetime.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] However, this duty cycling may result in high network latency, routing overhead, and neighbor discovery delays due to asynchronous sleep and wake-up scheduling.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] These limitations call for a countermeasure for duty-cycled wireless sensor networks which should minimize routing information, routing traffic load, and energy consumption.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers from Sungkyunkwan University have proposed a lightweight non-increasing delivery-latency interval routing referred as LNDIR.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] This scheme can discover minimum latency routes at each non-increasing delivery-latency interval instead of each time slot.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Simulation experiments demonstrated the validity of this novel approach in minimizing routing information stored at each sensor.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Furthermore, this novel routing can also guarantee the minimum delivery latency from each source to the sink.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Performance improvements of up to 12-fold and 11-fold are observed in terms of routing traffic load reduction and energy efficiency, respectively, as compared to existing schemes.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Operating systems for wireless sensor network nodes are typically less complex than general-purpose operating systems.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] They more strongly resemble embedded systems, for two reasons.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] First, wireless sensor networks are typically deployed with a particular application in mind, rather than as a general platform.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Second, a need for low costs and low power leads most wireless sensor nodes to have low-power microcontrollers ensuring that mechanisms such as virtual memory are either unnecessary or too expensive to implement.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] It is therefore possible to use embedded operating systems such as eCos or uC/OS for sensor networks.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] However, such operating systems are often designed with real-time properties.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS, developed by David Culler, is perhaps the first operating system specifically designed for wireless sensor networks.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS is based on an event-driven programming model instead of multithreading.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] TinyOS programs are composed of *event handlers* and *tasks* with run-to-completion semantics.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] When an external event occurs, such as an incoming data packet or a sensor reading, TinyOS signals the appropriate event handler to handle the event.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Event handlers can post tasks that are scheduled by the TinyOS kernel some time later.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] LiteOS is a newly developed OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides UNIX-like abstraction and support for the C programming language.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Contiki, developed by Adam Dunkels, is an OS which uses a simpler programming style in C while providing advances such as 6LoWPAN and Protothreads.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] RIOT (operating system) is a more recent real-time OS including similar functionality to Contiki.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] PreonVM is an OS for wireless sensor networks, which provides 6LoWPAN based on Contiki and support for the Java programming language.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Examples include Xively and the Wikisensing platform Archived 2021-06-09 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Such platforms simplify online collaboration between users over diverse data sets ranging from energy and environment data to that collected from transport services.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Other services include allowing developers to embed real-time graphs & widgets in websites; analyse and process historical data pulled from the data feeds; send real-time alerts from any datastream to control scripts, devices and environments.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] At present, agent-based modeling and simulation is the only paradigm which allows the simulation of complex behavior in the environments of wireless sensors (such as flocking).
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based simulation of wireless sensor and ad hoc networks is a relatively new paradigm.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Agent-based modelling was originally based on social simulation.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Network simulators like Opnet, Tetcos NetSim and NS can be used to simulate a wireless sensor network.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Network localization refers to the problem of estimating the location of wireless sensor nodes during deployments and in dynamic settings.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] For ultra-low power sensors, size, cost and environment precludes the use of Global Positioning System receivers on sensors.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] In 2000, Nirupama Bulusu, John Heidemann and Deborah Estrin first motivated and proposed a radio connectivity based system for localization of wireless sensor networks.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Subsequently, such localization systems have been referred to as range free localization systems, and many localization systems for wireless sensor networks have been subsequently proposed including AHLoS, APS, and Stardust.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Sensors and devices used in wireless sensor networks are state-of-the-art technology with the lowest possible price.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The sensor measurements we get from these devices are therefore often noisy, incomplete and inaccurate.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Researchers studying wireless sensor networks hypothesize that much more information can be extracted from hundreds of unreliable measurements spread across a field of interest than from a smaller number of high-quality, high-reliability instruments with the same total cost.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Macro-programming is a term coined by Matt Welsh.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] It refers to programming the entire sensor network as an ensemble, rather than individual sensor nodes.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Another way to macro-program a network is to view the sensor network as a database, which was popularized by the TinyDB system developed by Sam Madden.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Reprogramming is the process of updating the code on the sensor nodes.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The most feasible form of reprogramming is remote reprogramming whereby the code is disseminated wirelessly while the nodes are deployed.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Different reprogramming protocols exist that provide different levels of speed of operation, reliability, energy expenditure, requirement of code resident on the nodes, suitability to different wireless environments, resistance to DoS, etc.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Infrastructure-less architecture (i.e. no gateways are included, etc.) and inherent requirements (i.e. unattended working environment, etc.) of WSNs might pose several weak points that attract adversaries.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Therefore, security is a big concern when WSNs are deployed for special applications such as military and healthcare.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Owing to their unique characteristics, traditional security methods of computer networks would be useless (or less effective) for WSNs.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Hence, lack of security mechanisms would cause intrusions towards those networks.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] These intrusions need to be detected and mitigation methods should be applied.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] There have been important innovations in securing wireless sensor networks.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Most wireless embedded networks use omni-directional antennas and therefore neighbors can overhear communication in and out of nodes.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] This was used this to develop a primitive called "*local monitoring*" which was used for detection of sophisticated attacks, like blackhole or wormhole, which degrade the throughput of large networks to close-to-zero.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] This primitive has since been used by many researchers and commercial wireless packet sniffers.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] This was subsequently refined for more sophisticated attacks such as with collusion, mobility, and multi-antenna, multi-channel devices.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] If a centralized architecture is used in a sensor network and the central node fails, then the entire network will collapse, however the reliability of the sensor network can be increased by using a distributed control architecture.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] To provide nodes with backup in case of failure of the central node.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] There is also no centralised body to allocate the resources and they have to be self organized.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] The data gathered from wireless sensor networks is usually saved in the form of numerical data in a central base station.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] To reduce communication costs some algorithms remove or reduce nodes' redundant sensor information and avoid forwarding data that is of no use.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] This technique has been used, for instance, for distributed anomaly detection or distributed optimization.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] As nodes can inspect the data they forward, they can measure averages or directionality for example of readings from other nodes.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] For example, in sensing and monitoring applications, it is generally the case that neighboring sensor nodes monitoring an environmental feature typically register similar values.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] This kind of data redundancy due to the spatial correlation between sensor observations inspires techniques for in-network data aggregation and mining.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation reduces the amount of network traffic which helps to reduce energy consumption on sensor nodes.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] This is a form of in-network processing where sensor nodes are assumed to be unsecured with limited available energy, while the base station is assumed to be secure with unlimited available energy.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Aggregation complicates the already existing security challenges for wireless sensor networks and requires new security techniques tailored specifically for these scenarios.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Providing security to aggregate data in wireless sensor networks is known as *secure data aggregation in WSN*. were the first few works discussing techniques for secure data aggregation in wireless sensor networks.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Two main security challenges in secure data aggregation are confidentiality and integrity of data.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] While encryption is traditionally used to provide end to end confidentiality in wireless sensor network, the aggregators in a secure data aggregation scenario need to decrypt the encrypted data to perform aggregation.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] This exposes the plaintext at the aggregators, making the data vulnerable to attacks from an adversary.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Similarly an aggregator can inject false data into the aggregate and make the base station accept false data.
[src:wirelesshart/wireless-sensor-network] Thus, while data aggregation improves energy efficiency of a network, it complicates the existing security challenges.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] The protocol utilizes a time synchronized, self-organizing, and self-healing mesh architecture.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] The protocol employs Time Division Multiple Access (TDMA), dividing each second into 100 time slots of 10 milliseconds each, with the entire network synchronized across these slots to enable collision-free, deterministic communication.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] Combined with Frequency Hopping Spread Spectrum (FHSS), the protocol changes wireless channel with each time slot across 15 of the 16 available channels in the 2.4 GHz band, and supports channel blacklisting to avoid heavily congested frequencies.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] Each device in the network acts as a router, forwarding messages from other devices and providing multiple redundant communication paths.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] The network supports two routing modes: graph routing, in which paths are determined centrally by a network manager and distributed to field devices, and source routing, used primarily for diagnostics, in which the originating device specifies the full sequence of hops.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] The protocol supports operation in the 2.4 GHz ISM band using IEEE 802.15.4 standard radios.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] The underlying wireless technology is based on the work of Dust Networks' TSMP technology.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] WirelessHART was approved by a vote of the 210 member general HCF membership, ratified by the HCF Board of Directors, and introduced to the market in September 2007.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] Following its completed work on the WirelessHART standard in September 2007, the HCF offered International Society of Automation (ISA) an unrestricted, royalty-free copyright license, allowing the ISA100 committee access to the WirelessHART standard.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] Backward compatibility with the HART “user layer” allows transparent adaptation of HART compatible control systems and configuration tools to integrate new wireless networks and their devices, as well as continued use of proven configuration and system-integration work practices.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] It is estimated that 25 million HART field devices are installed worldwide, and approximately 3 million new wired HART devices are shipping each year.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] In September 2008, Emerson became the first process automation supplier to begin production shipments for its WirelessHART enabled products.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] During the summer of 2009 NAMUR, an international user association in the chemical and pharmaceutical processing industries, conducted a field test of WirelessHART to verify alignment with the NAMUR requirements for wireless automation in process applications.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] WirelessHart was approved by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in January 2009 with revision released in April 2010.
[src:wirelesshart/wirelesshart] The latest edition, version 2, was released in 2016 as IEC/PAS 62591:2016.
